                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I've been a lurker on this board for a while now, and ever since the day I created my toon I've really enjoyed what I felt to be my role in the game (CC, buffs, etc)... I was originally a druid but switched to a chanty because I had seen what they could do in a group and I wanted to learn more about it.  But I've gotta admit... I've seen all the complaints about high end playing and at the time some of the problems were put into the "cross that bridge when I come to it" file, but now that I am passing through the 50's and looking foward, all the complaints are legitimate.  
<br />

<br />
My sister plays a mage and we often discuss tactics and the necessity for them in determining how you play in different situations/zones.  It seems that (as has been said many times on this board and others) that in the newer content having an enchanter in group is hardly more than a convenience, not a necessity.  I understand that there are only 6 spots available, and that you simply cannot promise an enchanter that they are a requirement with so many neglected classes.  But in addition to nerfs on our spell lines (yes, I do mean charm), some of them have awkward gaps (no single target mezz for a mob our current level?  whuh?) which significantly cripple our ability to fulfill our duties in a group in some situations.  
<br />

<br />
Anyhow, my point was just to let all the /ranters know that I finally get where they're coming from... but I still love my chanty.  I hope that those who still play stick around a while longer, and that those who have retired continue to post so others can learn from their wisdom.  Enchanters are a kickass class, and anyone who has played one (whether they said F**K THIS and hung up their robe, or decided to push through it and keep hastling SOE) gets a high-five from me.  Ok... back to hiding in the shadows...</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
